":["15-18 years each","12-15 years each","15-18 years; 12-15 years","12-15 years; 15-18 years","20-25 years each"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe average lifetime of a \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal hip replacement (THR)\u003C/strong\u003E is typically 15-18 years, while a \u003Cstrong\u003Etotal knee replacement (TKR)\u003C/strong\u003E generally lasts 12-15 years. These estimates can vary based on individual patient factors and advancements in surgical techniques and materials.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Total hip replacements (THR) typically last 15-18 years on average.","Total knee replacements (TKR) generally last 12-15 years on average.","The longevity of joint replacements can vary based on factors such as patient activity level, weight, and surgical technique."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379","Ombregt, L. (2013). A System of Orthopaedic Medicine-E-Book: A System of Orthopaedic Medicine-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63868"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18392"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63868"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-11T09:40:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-11T09:40:50+10:30"},"r